Definition 3.3.12. Let $\mathbf{C}$ be a symmetric monoidal $(\infty,2)$-category, and let $R$ be a $\mathbf{E}^{2}_{\infty}$-algebra object of $\mathbf{C}$. An $R$-module is an object $M$ of $\mathbf{C}$ with a map $R\to\mathrm{End}_{\mathbf{C}}(M)$.
Definition 2.2.3. A map $p:X\to S$ is an inner $2$-fibration if it has the right lifting property with respect to all scaled anodyne maps.
Definition 3.1.9. If $\Phi$ is an operator category, define a complete Segal $\Phi$-operad to be a left fibration $p:\mathbf{X}\to\mathrm{N}({\mathbf{\Delta}}_{\Phi})^{op}$ such that a functor ${\mathbf{\Delta}}_{\Phi}^{op}\to\mathbf{Kan}$ classifying $p$ has all the three maps $p_{(\mathbf{n},I)}$, $s_{(\mathbf{n},I)}$, and $r$ defined above as equivalences. A map of complete Segal $\Phi$-operads is a map in the overcategory $({\mathrm{Set}}_{\mathbf{\Delta}})_{/\mathrm{N}({\mathbf{\Delta}}_{\Phi})^{op}}$.
Definition 3.3.16. Again, fix some $J^{0}_{\bullet}$, not necessarily $\langle 1\rangle$. An ideal of a $2$-ring $\mathbf{C}$ is a submodule of $\mathbf{C}$, when viewed as a module over itself.
Definition 2.2.6. A Cartesian $2$-fibration of scaled simplicial sets is a map $p:X\to S$ of scaled simplicial sets such that: • $p$ is an inner $2$-fibration whose underlying map of simplicial sets is a Cartesian fibration. • A thin $2$-simplex $s\to p(y)$ in $S$ can be pulled back to a thin $p$-Cartesian $2$-simplex $x\to y$ in $X$ such that $p(x)=s$.
Definition 3.2.7. A $2$-fold complete Segal $\Phi$-operad is a left $2$-fibration $p:\mathbf{X}^{\otimes}\to\mathrm{N}({\mathbf{\Delta}}_{\Phi}\boxtimes{\mathbf{% \Delta}}_{\Phi})^{op}$ such that if $\chi$ is its classifying map, then $p_{s,I},s_{s,I}$, and $r_{2}$ are all equivalences.
Definition 2.1.16. An $(\infty,2)$-category is a simplicial set with the right lifting property with respect to the scaled anodyne maps.
Definition 3.1.7. A $\Phi$-sequence is a pair $\mathbf{n}\in{\mathbf{\Delta}}$ and a functor $I:\mathbf{n}\to\Phi$, denoted by $[I_{0}\to\cdots\to I_{n}]$. A map of $\Phi$-sequences is a pair of maps map $(p,q):(\mathbf{n},I)\to(\mathbf{m},J)$ where $q$ is a natural transformation $q:I\to J\circ p$ such that for any $0\leq k\leq m$, the map $q_{k}:I_{k}\to J_{p(k)}$ is an interval inclusion, and for any $0\leq\sigma\leq\tau\leq m$, $J_{p(\tau)}\simeq J_{p(\sigma)}\times_{I_{\sigma}}I_{\tau}$. These form a category, denoted ${\mathbf{\Delta}}_{\Phi}$.
Definition 3.3.5. A $2$-ring is a $\mathbf{E}^{2}_{\infty}$-algebra object of $\mathbf{Mod}_{\mathbf{Sp}}(\mathcal{P}\mathrm{r^{L}})$.
Definition 2.8. If we let $\mathcal{F}=\{G(n)\subset F(n):n\in\mathbb{N}\}\cup\{F(0)\subset I\}$ Then the identification of Remark 2.5, $\mathcal{F}$ and Theorem 2.6 give a model structure on $s^{2}\textbf{Pre}(\mathscr{C})$ called the local complete Segal model structure. We call its weak equivalences local complete Segal equivalences. We call its fibrations Segal-injective fibrations.
Definition 1.2. Given a category C, its Discrete Nerve, $Disc(C)$ is defined to be the bisimplicial set $B(C)\tilde{\times}\Delta^{0}$. We write $I=Disc(B\pi(\Delta^{1}))$. Note that if n is the ordinal number category $Disc(\textbf{n})=\Delta^{n}\tilde{\times}\Delta^{0}=F(n)$, so that there is a map $F(0)\rightarrow I$ induced by the inclusion of the initial vertex $\textbf{0}\subset\pi(\Delta^{1})$.
Definition 2.2. Denote $s,t:Mor(A)\rightarrow Ob(A)$ the source and target maps. We will regard $Mor(A),Ob(A)$ as discrete simplicial presheaves. An $A$-Diagram is a simplicial presheaf map $\pi_{X}:X\rightarrow Ob(A)$, together with an ’action diagram’ $\xymatrix{X\times_{s}Mor(A)\ar[d]_{pr}\ar[r]^{m}&X\ar[d]_{\pi}\\ Mor(A)\ar[r]_{t}&Ob(A)}$ One further requires that $m$ respects compositions and identities. We denote by $s\textbf{Pre}(\mathscr{C})^{A}$, the category of A-diagrams, whose morphisms are natural transformations $\xymatrix{X\ar[rr]^{f}\ar[dr]_{\pi_{X}}&&Y\ar[dl]^{\pi_{Y}}\\ &Ob(A)&}$ that respect compositions and identities.
Definition 1.9. There are adjoint functors $k_{!}:s\textbf{Set}\leftrightarrows s\textbf{Set}:k^{!}$ where $k_{!}(X)=\underset{\underset{\Delta^{n}\rightarrow X}{\longrightarrow}}{lim}(B% \pi(\Delta^{n}))$ and $k^{!}(X)_{n}=hom(B\pi(\Delta^{n}),X)$
Definition 2.1. There is a site $\mathscr{C}/A$ whose objects are all pairs $(U,x)$, where $U$ is an object of $\mathscr{C}$ and $x\in Ob(A)(U)$. A morphism $(\alpha,f):(V,y)\rightarrow(U,x)$ in the category $\mathscr{C}/A$ is a pair consisting of a morphism $\alpha:V\rightarrow U$ of $\mathscr{C}$ along with a morphism $f:\alpha^{*}(x)\rightarrow y$ of $A(U)$. Given another morphism $(\gamma,g)$, the composite $(\alpha,f)\circ(\gamma,g)$ is defined by $(\alpha,f)\circ(\gamma,g)=(\alpha\gamma,g\cdot\gamma^{*}(f))$ There is a forgetful functor $c:\mathscr{C}/A\rightarrow\mathscr{C}$ which is defined by $(U,x)\mapsto U$. If the covering sieves for $\mathscr{C}/A$ are of the form $c^{-1}(S)$, where $S$ is a covering sieve for the topology on $\mathscr{C}$.
Definition 1.7. The Segal model structure is the left Bousfield localization of the Reedy model structure on $s^{2}\textbf{Set}$ along the set of maps $G(n)\subset F(n)$. The complete Segal model structure is the left Bousfield localization of the Reedy model structure on $s^{2}\textbf{Set}$ along the set of maps $G(n)\subset F(n)$ and the natural inclusion $F(0)\rightarrow I$, where $I$ is as in Definition 1.2. We call the fibrant objects of these model categories respectively Segal categories and complete Segal categories.
Definition 1.1. Write $F(k)=\Delta^{k,0}=\Delta^{k}\tilde{\times}\Delta^{0}$, and $\hat{F}(k)=\partial\Delta^{k}\tilde{\times}\Delta^{0}$.
Definition 1.4. Let $G(n)$ be the glued together string of 1-simplices $1\leq 2...\leq n$ inside $\Delta^{n}$ regarded as a bisimplicial set which is vertically discrete. Thus, there are natural inclusions $G(n)\subseteq F(n)$.
Definition 2.8. (BRC ) Let $(X,\delta)$ be an approach space. An approach prime of $(X,\delta)$ is a regular function $\phi$ subject to the following conditions: 1. $\inf_{x\in X}\phi(x)=0$; 2. for any regular functions $\xi$ and $\psi$, if $\min\{\xi,\psi\}\leq\phi$ then either $\xi\leq\phi$ or $\psi\leq\phi$.
Definition 2.3. (RL89 ; RL97 ) An approach space is a pair $(X,\delta)$ consisting of a set $X$ and a map $\delta:X\times 2^{X}\longrightarrow[0,\infty]$, called an approach distance on $X$, subject to the following conditions: (A1) $\delta(x,\{x\})=0$, (A2) $\delta(x,\varnothing)=\infty$, (A3) $\delta(x,A\cup B)=\min\{\delta(x,A),\delta(x,B)\}$, (A4) $\delta(x,A)\leq\delta(x,B)+\sup_{b\in B}\delta(b,A)$, for all $x\in X$ and $A,B\in 2^{X}$.
Definition 4.13. (BvBR1998 ; Wagner97 ) Let $\{x_{\lambda}\}$ be a net in a generalized metric space $(X,d)$. An element $x\in X$ is a Yoneda limit (a.k.a. liminf) of $\{x_{\lambda}\}$ if $d(x,y)=\inf_{\lambda}\sup_{\sigma\geq\lambda}d(x_{\sigma},y)$ for all $y\in X$.
Definition 6.34. A generalized metric space $(X,d)$ is Smyth completable if all flat weights of $(X,d)$ are Cauchy.
Definition 2.1. (Lawvere73 ) A generalized metric space is a pair $(X,d)$ consisting of a set $X$ and a map $d:X\times X\longrightarrow[0,\infty]$ such that for all $x,y,z\in X$, (1) $d(x,x)=0$, (2) $d(x,y)+d(y,z)\geq d(x,z)$. The map $d$ is called a generalized metric on $X$, the value $d(x,y)$ the distance from $x$ to $y$.
Definition 6.38. A generalized metric space $(X,d)$ is Smyth complete if for each flat weight $\phi$ of $(X,d)$, there is a unique $a\in X$ such that $\phi=d(-,a)$.
Definition 4.14. (BvBR1998 ; Wagner97 ) A generalized metric space is Yoneda complete if each forward Cauchy net in it has a Yoneda limit.
Definition 2.9. (BRC ) An approach space $(X,\delta)$ is sober if for each approach prime $\phi$ of $(X,\delta)$, there exists a unique $x\in X$ such that $\phi=\delta(-,\{x\})$.
Definition 4.18. Let $(X,d)$ be a generalized metric space, $\phi:X\longrightarrow[0,\infty]$ a weight of $(X,d)$. 1. (Lawvere73 ) $\phi$ is Cauchy if there is a coweight $\psi:X\longrightarrow[0,\infty]$ of $(X,d)$ such that $\phi\otimes\psi=0$ and $\phi(x)+\psi(y)\geq d(x,y)$ for all $x,y\in X$. 2. (SV2005 ) $\phi$ is flat if $\inf_{x\in X}\phi(x)=0$ and $\phi\otimes\max\{\psi_{1},\psi_{2}\}=\max\{\phi\otimes\psi_{1},\phi\otimes\psi% _{2}\}$ for any coweights $\psi_{1},\psi_{2}$ on $(X,d)$.
Definition 2.2. We say an element $x\in S$ is positive if $x^{2}>x$, and negative if $x^{2}<x$. We will use $S^{+}$ to denote the positive elements of $S$, and $S^{-}$ to denote the negative elements.
Definition 2.5. Elements $x,y\in S$ with $x>y$ form an anomalous pair if either $x^{n}<y^{n+1}\ \ \text{ or }\ \ y^{n}>x^{n+1}\ \ \text{ for every n}\in\mathbb% {N}.$ The former case implies that $x,y\in S^{+}$ and the latter implies that $x,y\in S^{-}$. If no pair in $S$ is anomalous, we shall call $S$ an non-anomalous semigroup, or an NAS for short.
Definition 2.6. A semigroup is Archimedean if 1. For every $x,y\in S^{+}$ there exists an $n\in\mathbb{N}$ so that $x<y^{n}.$ 2. For every $x,y\in S^{-}$ there exists an $n\in\mathbb{N}$ so that $x>y^{n}.$
Definition 3.1. A positive morphism $f$ between two totally ordered semigroups is a group homomorphism that is an order embedding: $f(x+y)=f(x)+f(y),\ \ \ x<y\implies f(x)<f(y).$ A negative morphism is a group homomorphism that reverses the order $x<y\implies f(x)>f(y).$
Definition 2.1. A totally ordered semigroup (which we will abbreviate to TOS) is a set $S$ along with a binary relation $<$ and a law of composition so that for any $x,y,z\in S$ 1. If $x<y$ and $y<z$ then $x<z$ 2. Exactly one of the following holds: $x<y$, or $x=y$, or $x>y.$ 3. $(xy)z=x(yz)$ 4. If $x<y$, then $xz<yz$ and $zx<zy.$
Definition 2. Let $S$ and $T$ be two species. An isomorphism $\psi$ from $S$ to $T$ is a family of bijections $\psi_{X}:S(X)\rightarrow T(X)$, such that, for any bijection $\sigma:Y\rightarrow X$, the diagram $S(X)$$S(Y)$$T(X)$$T(Y)$$S(\sigma)$$\psi_{X}$$\psi_{Y}$$T(\sigma)$ commutes. If there exists an isomorphism from $S$ to $T$, we say that they $S$ and $T$ are isomorphic and we write $S\simeq T$.
Definition 3. Let $S$ and $T$ be species, $X$ an arbitrary finite set and $\sigma:Y\rightarrow X$ a bijection. The sum of $S$ and $T$ is the species $S+T$ defined as $(S+T)(X)=S(X)+T(X)\vspace{-0.1cm}$ and $(S+T)({\sigma})(f)=\left\{\begin{array}[]{cl}S({\sigma})(f)&\mbox{if }f\in S(X% )\\ T({\sigma})(f)&\mbox{if }f\in T(X)\,.\\ \end{array}\right.\vspace{0.1cm}$ The product of $S$ and $T$ is the species $S\cdot T$ defined as $(S\cdot T)(X)=\sum_{(X_{1},X_{2})}S(X_{1})\times T(X_{2}),\vspace{-0.1cm}$ with the disjoint sum being taken over all binary decompositions $(X_{1},X_{2})$ of $X$. The action of $S\cdot T$ on $\sigma$ is given as $(S\cdot T)(\sigma)(f,g)=(S(\sigma_{1})(f),T(\sigma_{2})(g)),$ where $\sigma_{i}=\sigma|^{X_{i}}$, $i=1,2.$
Definition 1. A species (of structures) is a functor $S:{\bf Bij}^{op}\rightarrow{\bf Set}$.
Definition 10. Let $S$ and $T$ be species, $X$ a finite set and $\sigma:Y\rightarrow X$ a bijection. The triangle product (or, shorter, the $\blacktriangle$-product) of $S$ and $T$ is the species $S\blacktriangle T$ defined as $S\blacktriangle T=\partial S\cdot\partial T.\vspace{-0.1cm}$ Therefore, for a finite set $X$, $(S\blacktriangle T)(X)=\sum_{(X_{1},X_{2})}\{(f,g)\,|\,f\in S(X_{1}+\{\ast_{X_% {1}}\}),g\in T(X_{2}+\{\ast_{X_{2}}\})\},\vspace{-0.15cm}$ and, for $(f,g)\in(S\blacktriangle T)(X)$, where $f\in\partial S(X_{1})=S(X_{1}+\{\ast_{X_{1}}\})$ and $g\in\partial S(X_{2})=S(X_{2}+\ast_{X_{2}})$, $(S\blacktriangle T)(\sigma)(f,g)=(S(\sigma_{1}^{+})(f),T(\sigma_{2}^{+})(g)),% \vspace{-0.1cm}$ where $\sigma_{1}=\sigma|^{X_{1}}$, $\sigma_{2}=\sigma|^{X_{2}}$, and $\sigma_{i}^{+}$ are the $\partial$-extensions of $\sigma_{i}$, $i=1,2$.
Definition 13 (exchangeable-output, monoid-like). A non-unitary cyclic operad is a quadruple $(S,\nu,\eta_{1},D)$, such that $(S,\nu,\eta_{1})$ is a non-unitary (monoid-like) operad, and the natural transformation $D:\partial S\rightarrow\partial S$ satisfies the following laws: (D0) $D\circ{\eta}^{\partial S}={\eta}^{\partial S}$, (D1) $D^{2}={\it id}_{\partial S}$, (D2) $(\partial D\circ{\tt ex})^{3}={\it id}_{\partial\partial S},$ as well as the laws (D3) and (D4) given by commutative diagrams $\partial(\partial S)\cdot S$$\partial(\partial S)\cdot S$$\partial S$$\partial S$$({\tt ex}\circ\partial D\circ{\tt ex})\cdot{\it id}$$\nu_{3}$$\nu_{3}$$D$and$\partial S\cdot\partial S$$\partial S\cdot\partial S$$\partial S$$\partial S\cdot\partial S$$\partial S$$D\cdot D$$\nu_{4}$${\tt c}$$D$$\nu_{4}$ respectively, where $\nu_{3}$ and $\nu_{4}$ are induced from $\nu$ as follows: ${\small\begin{array}[]{cl}\nu_{3}:\partial\partial S\cdot S\xrightarrow{% \enspace i_{l}\enspace}\partial\partial S\cdot S+\partial S\cdot\partial% \partial S\xrightarrow{\enspace\varphi^{-1}\enspace}\partial(\partial S\cdot% \partial S)\xrightarrow{\enspace\partial\nu\enspace}\partial S,&\mbox{and}\\ \nu_{4}:\partial S\cdot\partial S\xrightarrow{\enspace i_{r}\enspace}\partial% \partial S\cdot S+\partial S\cdot\partial\partial S\xrightarrow{\enspace% \varphi^{-1}\enspace}\partial(\partial S\cdot\partial S)\xrightarrow{\enspace% \partial\nu\enspace}\partial S.&\end{array}}$
Definition 7 (componential). An operad is a species ${\mathcal{O}}:{\bf Bij}^{op}\rightarrow{\bf Set}$, together with a distinguished element ${\it id}_{x}\in{\mathcal{O}}(\{x\})$ that exists for each singleton $\{x\}$, and a partial composition operation $\circ_{x}:{\mathcal{O}}(X)\times{\mathcal{O}}(Y)\rightarrow{\mathcal{O}}((X% \backslash\{x\})\cup Y),\vspace{-0.1cm}$ defined for arbitrary non-empty finite set $X$, an arbitrary set $Y$ and $x\in X$ such that $(X\backslash\{x\})\cap Y=\emptyset$. These data satisfy the axioms given below. Associativity. For $f\in{\mathcal{O}}(X)$, $g\in{\mathcal{O}}(Y)$ and $h\in{\mathcal{O}}(Z)$, the following two equalities hold: [A1] $(f\circ_{x}g)\circ_{y}h=(f\circ_{y}h)\circ_{x}g$, where $x,y\in X$, and [A2] $(f\circ_{x}g)\circ_{y}h=f\circ_{x}(g\circ_{y}h)$, where $x\in X$ and $y\in Y$. Equivariance. For bijections $\sigma_{1}:X^{\prime}\rightarrow X$ and $\sigma_{2}:Y^{\prime}\rightarrow Y$, and $f\in{\mathcal{C}}(X)$ and $g\in{\mathcal{C}}(Y)$, the following equality holds: [EQ] $f^{\sigma_{1}}\circ_{\sigma_{1}^{-1}(x)}\,\,g^{\sigma_{2}}=(f\circ_{x}g)^{\sigma}$, where $\sigma=\sigma_{1}|^{X\backslash\{x\}}\cup\sigma_{2}$. Unitality. For $f\in\mathcal{C}(X)$ and $x\in X$, the following two equalities hold: [U1] ${\it id}_{y}\circ_{y}f=f$, and [U2] $f\circ_{x}{\it id}_{x}=f$. Moreover, the unit elements are preserved under the action of ${\mathcal{C}}(\sigma)$, i.e. [UP] ${id_{x}}^{\sigma}=id_{u}$, for any two singletons $\{x\}$ and $\{u\}$, and a bijection $\sigma:\{u\}\rightarrow\{x\}$.
Definition 5. The derivative of $S$ is the species $\partial S$ defined as $(\partial S)(X)=S(X+\{\ast_{X}\}),\vspace{-0.1cm}$ where $\ast_{X}$ is an element chosen outside of $X$. The action of $\partial S$ on $\sigma$ is defined as $(\partial S)(\sigma)(f)=S(\sigma^{+})(f),\vspace{-0.1cm}$ where $\sigma^{+}:Y+\{\ast_{Y}\}\rightarrow X+\{\ast_{X}\}$ is such that $\sigma^{+}(y)=\sigma(y)$ for $y\in Y$ and $\sigma^{+}(\ast_{Y})=\ast_{X}$. We shall refer to $\sigma^{+}$ as the $\partial$-extension of $\sigma$.
Definition 11 (entries-only, monoid-like). A non-unitary cyclic operad is a triple $(S,\rho,\eta_{2})$ of a species $S$, such that $S(\emptyset)=S(\{x\})=\emptyset$ for all singletons $\{x\}$, a morphism $\rho:S\blacktriangle S\rightarrow S$, called the multiplication, and a morphism $\eta_{2}:E_{2}\rightarrow S$, called the unit, such that (CA1) $\rho_{2}\circ\gamma=\rho_{1}$, where $\rho_{1}$ and $\rho_{2}$ are induced from $\rho$ as follows: aaaaka- $\rho_{1}:(S\blacktriangle S)\blacktriangle S+S\blacktriangle(S\blacktriangle S% )+(S\blacktriangle S)\blacktriangle S\rightarrow S$ is determined by ${\footnotesize\begin{array}[]{llllll}&&&&&\rho_{11}:(\partial\partial S\cdot% \partial S)\cdot\partial S\xrightarrow{i\cdot{\it id}}(\partial\partial S\cdot% \partial S+\partial S\cdot\partial\partial S)\cdot\partial S\xrightarrow{% \varphi^{-1}\cdot{\it id}}\partial(\partial S\cdot\partial S)\cdot\partial S% \xrightarrow{\partial\rho\cdot{\it id}}\partial S\cdot\partial S\xrightarrow{% \rho}S\\ &&&&&\rho_{12}:(\partial S\cdot\partial\partial S)\cdot\partial S\xrightarrow{% i\cdot{\it id}}(\partial\partial S\cdot\partial S+\partial S\cdot\partial% \partial S)\cdot\partial S\xrightarrow{\varphi^{-1}\cdot{\it id}}\partial(% \partial S\cdot\partial S)\cdot\partial S\xrightarrow{\partial\rho\cdot{\it id% }}\partial S\cdot\partial S\xrightarrow{\rho}S\\ &&&&&\rho_{13}:\partial S\cdot(\partial\partial S\cdot\partial S)\xrightarrow{% {\it id}\cdot i}\partial S\cdot(\partial\partial S\cdot\partial S+\partial S% \cdot\partial\partial S)\xrightarrow{{\it id}\cdot\varphi^{-1}}\partial S\cdot% \partial(\partial S\cdot\partial S)\xrightarrow{{\it id}\cdot\partial\rho}% \partial S\cdot\partial S\xrightarrow{\rho}S\\ &&&&&\rho_{14}:\partial S\cdot(\partial S\cdot\partial\partial S)\xrightarrow{% {\it id}\cdot i}\partial S\cdot(\partial\partial S\cdot\partial S+\partial S% \cdot\partial\partial S)\xrightarrow{{\it id}\cdot\varphi^{-1}}\partial S\cdot% \partial(\partial S\cdot\partial S)\xrightarrow{{\it id}\cdot\partial\rho}% \partial S\cdot\partial S\xrightarrow{\rho}S\\ &&&&&\rho_{15}=\rho_{11}\mbox{ \enspace\enspace and \enspace\enspace}\rho_{16}% =\rho_{12}\end{array}}$ aaaaka- $\rho_{2}:S\blacktriangle(S\blacktriangle S)+(S\blacktriangle S)\blacktriangle S% +S\blacktriangle(S\blacktriangle S)\rightarrow S$ is determined by aaaaaaaiaka $\rho_{21}=\rho_{11},\enspace\enspace\rho_{22}=\rho_{23}=\rho_{13},\enspace% \enspace\rho_{24}=\rho_{25}=\rho_{14}\enspace\enspace\mbox{ and }\enspace% \enspace\rho_{26}=\rho_{12}$, aaaaaaka and (CA2) $\eta_{2}$ satisfies the coherence condition given by the commutation of the following diagram $E_{2}\blacktriangle S$$S\blacktriangle S$$S^{\bullet}$$S$$\eta_{2}\blacktriangle{\it id}_{S}$$\lambda_{S}^{\blacktriangle}$$\rho$${\pi_{1}}_{S}$ where $\lambda_{S}^{\blacktriangle}$ and $\kappa_{S}^{\blacktriangle}$ are the isomorphisms from Lemma 7, and ${{\pi_{1}}_{S}}_{X}$ is the first projection. Convention 4. In the remaining of the paper we shall work only with non-unitary cyclic operads. To make things shorter, we shall refer to them simply as cyclic operads.
Definition 8 (monoid-like). An operad is a triple $(S,\nu,\eta_{1})$ of a species $S$, a morphism$\nu:S\star S\rightarrow S$, called the multiplication, and a morphism $\eta_{1}:E_{1}\rightarrow S$, called the unit, such that [OA1] $\nu_{2}\circ\beta=\nu_{1}$, where $\nu_{1}$ and $\nu_{2}$ are induced by $\nu$ as follows: aaaaka- $\nu_{1}:(S\star S)\star S+S\star(S\star S)\rightarrow S$ is determined by ${\footnotesize\begin{array}[]{llllll}&&&&&\nu_{11}:(\partial\partial S\cdot S)% \cdot S\xrightarrow{\enspace i_{l}\cdot{\it id}\enspace}(\partial\partial S% \cdot S+\partial S\cdot\partial S)\cdot\partial S\xrightarrow{\enspace\varphi^% {-1}\cdot{\it id}\enspace}\partial(\partial S\cdot S)\cdot S\xrightarrow{% \enspace\partial\nu\cdot{\it id}\enspace}\partial S\cdot S\xrightarrow{% \enspace\nu\enspace}S,\\ &&&&&\nu_{12}:(\partial S\cdot\partial S)\cdot S\xrightarrow{\enspace i_{r}% \cdot{\it id}\enspace}(\partial\partial S\cdot S+\partial S\cdot\partial S)% \cdot\partial S\xrightarrow{\enspace\varphi^{-1}\cdot{\it id}\enspace}\partial% (\partial S\cdot S)\cdot S\xrightarrow{\enspace\partial\nu\cdot{\it id}% \enspace}\partial S\cdot S\xrightarrow{\enspace\nu\enspace}S,\\ &&&&&\nu_{13}:\partial S\cdot(\partial S\cdot S)\xrightarrow{\enspace{\it id}% \cdot\nu\enspace}\partial S\cdot S\xrightarrow{\enspace\nu\enspace}S,\mbox{ % and}\end{array}}$ iiiaaia- $\nu_{2}:S\star(S\star S)+(S\star S)\star S\rightarrow S$ is determined by ${\footnotesize\begin{array}[]{llllll}&&&&&\nu_{21}=\nu_{11},\enspace\enspace% \nu_{22}=\nu_{13}\enspace\enspace\mbox{ and }\enspace\enspace\nu_{23}=\nu_{12}% ,\end{array}}\vspace{-0.1cm}$ iiaaia and [OA2] $\eta_{1}$ satisfies coherence conditions given by the commutation of the following diagram: $E_{1}\star S$$S\star S$$S\star E_{1}$$S$$\eta_{1}\star{\it id}_{S}$${\it id}_{S}\star\eta_{1}$$\lambda_{S}^{\star}$$\rho_{S}^{\star}$$\nu$
Definition 4. Let $S$ and $T$ be species, $X$ a finite set, $\sigma:Y\rightarrow X$ a bijection and $D(X)$ the set of all decompositions of $X$. The substitution product of $S$ and $T$ is the species $S\circ T$ defined as $(S\circ T)(X)=\sum_{\pi\in D(X)}\bigg{(}S(\pi)\times\prod_{p\in\pi}T(p)\bigg{)% }.\vspace{-0.1cm}$ For an arbitrary $h=(\pi,f,(g_{p})_{p\in\pi})\in(S\circ T)(X)$, the action of $S\circ T$ on $\sigma$ is defined by $(S\circ T)(\sigma)(h)=(\overline{\pi},\overline{f},(\overline{g}_{\overline{p}% })_{\overline{p}\in\overline{\pi}}),\vspace{-0.1cm}$ where $\overline{\pi}$ is the decomposition of $Y$ induced by $\sigma$, $\overline{f}=S(\overline{\sigma})(f)$, where $\overline{\sigma}:\overline{\pi}\rightarrow\pi$ is induced by $\sigma$, and, for each $\overline{p}\in\overline{\pi}$, $\overline{g}_{\overline{p}}=T(\sigma|^{p})(g_{p})$.
Definition 6. Let $S$ be a species. The species $S^{\bullet}$, spelled $S$ dot, is defined as follows $S^{\bullet}(X)=S(X)\times X.$ For a pair $s=(f,x)\in S(X)\times X$, the action of $S^{\bullet}$ on a bijection $\sigma:Y\rightarrow X$ is carried out by setting $S^{\bullet}(\sigma)(s)=(S(\sigma)(f),\sigma^{-1}(x)).$
Definition 9 (entries-only, componential). A non-unitary cyclic operad is a species${\mathcal{C}}:{\bf Bij}^{op}\rightarrow{\bf Set}$, such that ${\mathcal{C}}(\emptyset)={\mathcal{C}}(\{x\})=\emptyset$ for all singletons $\{x\}$, together with a distinguished element ${\it id}_{x,y}\in{\mathcal{C}}(\{x,y\})$ for each two-element set $\{x,y\}$, and a partial composition operation ${{{}_{x}\circ_{y}}}:{\mathcal{C}}(X)\times{\mathcal{C}}(Y)\rightarrow{\mathcal% {C}}(X\backslash\{x\}+Y\backslash\{y\}),\vspace{-0.1cm}$ defined for arbitrary non-empty finite sets $X$ and $Y$ and elements $x\in X$ and $y\in Y$, such that $(X\backslash\{x\})\cap(Y\backslash\{y\})=\emptyset.$ These data must satisfy the axioms given below. Parallel associativity. For $f\in{\mathcal{C}}(X)$, $g\in{\mathcal{C}}(Y)$ and $h\in{\mathcal{C}}(Z)$, the following equality holds: (A1) $(f\,{{}_{x}\circ_{y}}\,\,g)\,\,{{}_{u}\circ_{z}}\,h=(f{{}_{u}\circ_{z}}\,\,h)% \,\,{{}_{x}\circ_{y}}\,g$, where $x,u\in X$, $y\in Y,$ $z\in Z$. Equivariance. For bijections $\sigma_{1}:X^{\prime}\rightarrow X$ and $\sigma_{2}:Y^{\prime}\rightarrow Y$, and $f\in{\mathcal{C}}(X)$ and $g\in{\mathcal{C}}(Y)$, the following equality holds: (EQ) $f^{\sigma_{1}}\,\,{{}_{{{\sigma_{1}^{-1}}(x)}}\circ_{\sigma_{2}^{-1}(y)}}\,\,g% ^{\sigma_{2}}=(f{{}_{x}\circ_{y}}\,\,g)^{\sigma}$, where $\sigma=\sigma_{1}|^{X\backslash\{x\}}\cup\sigma_{2}|^{Y\backslash\{y\}}$. Unitality. For $f\in\mathcal{C}(X)$ and $x\in X$, the following equality holds: (U1) ${\it id}_{x,y}\,\,{{}_{y}\circ_{x}}\,\,f=f$. Moreover, the unit elements are preserved under the action of ${\mathcal{C}}(\sigma)$, i.e. (UP) ${id_{x,y}}^{\sigma}=id_{u,v}$, for any bijection $\sigma:\{u,v\}\rightarrow\{x,y\}$.
Definition 12 (exchangeable-output, componential). A non-unitary cyclic operad is a non-unitary (componential) operad ${\mathcal{O}}$, enriched with actions $D^{\mathcal{O}}_{x}:{\mathcal{O}}(X)\rightarrow{\mathcal{O}}(X),\vspace{-0.1cm}$ defined for all $x\in X$ and subject to the axioms given below, wherein, for each of the axioms, we assume that $f\in{\mathcal{O}}(X)$. Preservation of units. (DID) $D^{\mathcal{O}}_{x}({\it id}_{x})={\it id}_{x}$. Inverse. For $x\in X$, (DIN) $D^{\mathcal{O}}_{x}(D^{\mathcal{O}}_{x}(f))=f$. Equivariance. For $x\in X$ and an arbitrary bijection $\sigma:Y\rightarrow X$, (DEQ) $D_{x}(f)^{\sigma}=D_{\sigma^{-1}(x)}(f^{\sigma})$. Exchange. For $x,y\in X$ and a bijection $\sigma:X\rightarrow X$ that renames $x$ to $y$ and $y$ to $x$, (DEX) $D^{\mathcal{O}}_{x}(f)^{\sigma}=D^{\mathcal{O}}_{x}(D^{\mathcal{O}}_{y}(f)).$ Compatibility with operadic compositions. For $g\in{\mathcal{O}}(Y)$, the following equality holds: (DC1) $D^{\mathcal{O}}_{y}(f\circ_{x}g)=D^{\mathcal{O}}_{y}(f)\circ_{x}g$, where $y\in X\backslash\{x\}$, and (DC2) $D^{\mathcal{O}}_{y}(f\circ_{x}g)=D^{\mathcal{O}}_{y}(g)^{\sigma_{1}}\circ_{v}D% ^{\mathcal{O}}_{x}(f)^{\sigma_{2}}$, where $y\in Y$, $\sigma_{1}:Y\backslash\{y\}+\{v\}\rightarrow Y$ is a bijection(DC2) that renames $y$ to $v$ and $\sigma_{2}:X\backslash\{x\}+\{y\}\rightarrow X$ is a bijection that renames $x$ to $y$.
Definition 4.6. (1) A linear category $\mathfrak{a}$ is generated by subsets $X(A,A^{\prime})\subseteq\mathfrak{a}(A,A^{\prime})$ if every element of $\mathfrak{a}$ can be written as a linear sum of products of elements in $X$. (2) A $\mathbb{Z}$ algebra $\mathfrak{a}$ is generated in certain degrees $D\subseteq\mathbb{N}$ if it is generated by $X$ with $X(n,m)=\varnothing$ unless $n-m\in D$. (3) A $\mathbb{Z}$-algebra $\mathfrak{a}$ is finitely generated if it is generated by $X$ such that for all $m$ the set $\cup_{d\in\mathbb{N}}X(m+d,m)$ is finite. (4) A $\mathbb{Z}$-algebra $\mathfrak{a}$ is connected if $\mathfrak{a}(n,n)\cong k$ for all $n$.
Definition 3.1. Suppose $\mathcal{T}_{\mathfrak{a}}$ and $\mathcal{T}_{\mathfrak{c}}$ are localizing. The functor $\phi:(\mathfrak{a},\mathcal{T}_{\mathfrak{a}})\longrightarrow(\mathfrak{c},% \mathcal{T}_{\mathfrak{c}})$ is called continuous provided that $\phi^{\ast}:\mathsf{Mod}(\mathfrak{c})\longrightarrow\mathsf{Mod}(\mathfrak{a})$ preserves sheaves, and hence restricts to a functor $\phi_{s}:\mathsf{Sh}(\mathfrak{c},\mathcal{T}_{\mathfrak{c}})\longrightarrow% \mathsf{Sh}(\mathfrak{a},\mathcal{T}_{\mathfrak{a}})$.
Definition 3.4. Consider a linear functor $\phi:\mathfrak{a}\longrightarrow\mathfrak{c}$. (1) Suppose $\mathfrak{c}$ is endowed with a cover system $\mathcal{T}_{\mathfrak{c}}$. We say that $\phi:\mathfrak{a}\longrightarrow(\mathfrak{c},\mathcal{T}_{\mathfrak{c}})$ satisfies (G) if for every $C\in\mathfrak{c}$ there is a covering family $(\phi(A_{i})\longrightarrow C)_{i}$ for $\mathcal{T}_{\mathfrak{c}}$. (2) Suppose $\mathfrak{a}$ is endowed with a cover system $\mathcal{T}_{\mathfrak{a}}$. We say that $\phi:(\mathfrak{a},\mathcal{T}_{\mathfrak{a}})\longrightarrow\mathfrak{c}$ satisfies (F) if for every $c:\phi(A)\longrightarrow\phi(A^{\prime})$ in $\mathfrak{c}$ there exists a covering family $a_{i}:A_{i}\longrightarrow A$ for $\mathcal{T}_{\mathfrak{a}}$ and $f_{i}:A_{i}\longrightarrow A^{\prime}$ with $c\phi(a_{i})=\phi({f}_{i})$; (FF) if for every $a:A\longrightarrow A^{\prime}$ in $\mathfrak{a}$ with $\phi(a)=0$ there exists a covering family $a_{i}:A_{i}\longrightarrow A$ for $\mathcal{T}_{\mathfrak{a}}$ with $aa_{i}=0$. (3) Suppose $\mathfrak{a}$ and $\mathfrak{c}$ are endowed with cover systems $\mathcal{T}_{\mathfrak{a}}$ and $\mathcal{T}_{\mathfrak{c}}$ respectively. We say that $\phi:(\mathfrak{a},\mathcal{T}_{\mathfrak{a}})\longrightarrow(\mathfrak{c},% \mathcal{T}_{\mathfrak{c}})$ satisfies (LC) if $\phi$ satisfies (G) with respect to $\mathcal{T}_{\mathfrak{c}}$, (F) and (FF) with respect to $\mathcal{T}_{\mathfrak{a}}$, and we further have $\mathcal{T}_{\mathfrak{a}}=\phi^{-1}\mathcal{T}_{\mathfrak{c}}$.
Definition 2.1. Consider $\mathcal{H}\subseteq\mathrm{Ob}(\mathcal{C})$ and $C\in\mathcal{C}$. An ascending filtration of $C$ consists of an ordinal $\alpha$ and a collection of subobjects $(M_{\beta})_{\beta\leq\alpha}$ of $C$ such that $M_{0}=0$, $i\leq j$ implies $M_{i}\subseteq M_{j}$, $M_{\beta}=\cup_{\gamma<\beta}M_{\gamma}$ if $\beta$ is a limit ordinal, and $M_{\alpha}=C$. An ascending filtration $(M_{\beta})_{\beta\leq\alpha}$ of $C$ is called an $\mathcal{H}$-filtration provided that $M_{\beta+1}/M_{\beta}\in\mathcal{H}$ for all $\beta<\alpha$, and in this case $C$ is called $\mathcal{H}$-filtered.
Definition 3.2. [21, Def. 2.11] The functor $\phi:(\mathfrak{a},\mathcal{T}_{\mathfrak{a}})\longrightarrow(\mathfrak{c},% \mathcal{T}_{\mathfrak{c}})$ is called cocontinuous provided that for every $A\in\mathfrak{a}$ and $R\in\mathcal{T}_{\mathfrak{c}}(\phi(A))$ there exists $S\in\mathcal{T}_{\mathfrak{a}}(A)$ with $\phi S\subseteq R$.
Definition 4.2. Consider Grothendieck categories $\mathcal{C}$ and $\mathcal{D}$. The tensor product $\mathcal{C}\boxtimes\mathcal{D}$ is the following Grothendieck category, defined up to equivalence of categories: for arbitrary LC morphisms $u:(\mathfrak{a},\mathcal{T}_{\mathfrak{a}})\longrightarrow\mathcal{C}$ and $v:(\mathfrak{b},\mathcal{T}_{\mathfrak{b}})\longrightarrow\mathcal{D}$, we put $\mathcal{C}\boxtimes\mathcal{D}=\mathsf{Sh}(\mathfrak{a}\otimes\mathfrak{b},% \mathcal{T}_{\mathfrak{a}}\boxtimes\mathcal{T}_{\mathfrak{b}}).$
